<i>Posted by Justynn Thyme on 04-09-2001 12:14 AM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>*I posted this to the EQ QA board, but chances of it being answered are probably similar to my rolling abilities*<br>
<br>
Throughout my time playing everquest, I have noticed the random number generator to be VERY splotchy, both in trade skills, weapon skills, and in /random.<br>
<br>
In trade skills, I will be bored out of my mind making items trying to raise my skill (Which is another issue... what a waste of time!) and I will make 30 items without a skill increase, followed by 6 failures in a row, followed by 30 more increases, and then eventually I will usually get a skill increase, and *another increase* within 5 attempts<br>
<br>
Same thing in melee combat. Everyone goes on streaks of hits, then streaks of misses... and if your weapon skills are not maxed, you always go on small streaks of upgrades<br>
<br>
/random:<br>
<br>
Now this is by gripe. I am a BAD roller. I sat in gfay, and /random 100'd over and over again, recorded 500 numbers... ran the log through a script and plugged them into an excel spreadsheet. out of 500 rolls, 47 of them were above 35, and 32 of them were above 10.  That means in a /random 100, reapeted 500 times, I had 418 rolls between 10 and 35... suspicios? I think so!<br>
<br>
I then repeated the test, and had almost identical results, but the range was 15 and 50 this time, with almost no rolls outside that range.<br>
<br>
I then had a friend who is notorious for winning rolls run this test, and I logged his results. 500 rolls, and he had a grand total of 72 rolls under 80<br>
<br>
How can this be fair? Does our connection make a difference in how we roll? I have not won a roll on an item since I was level 38, 9 months ago, while I have had the same people beat me over and over again<FONT face="arial, helvetica" size="2"><br>
