<i>Posted by Fadetree on 04-09-2001 02:28 PM:</i>

<p><b> </b></p>

<p>Well, there are several very good random number algorithms circulating out there, whose mathematical properties are well understood. External sources of randomness ( 'entropy' ) are easily obtainable, especially on UNIX/Linux boxes. So for the RnG ( oh my gosh thats short for ranger eek ) that VI is using to behave the way it does means that either they aren't using commonly accepeted RnG code, or are doing something else funky. I remember in a MUD I wrote I played around with the RnG quite a bit, trying to add in factors ( such as a 'luck' factor calced from attributes ), and doing things like breaking a 0-100 roll down into 5 seperate 0-20 rolls and adding ( produces a bell curve distribution ), rolling 3 times and averaging, or picking the highest ( skews average upwards ), etc. My point is that a good RnG is easy to do, so they must be jacking around with the results in some way that produces the streaky nature. Hell, the streakiness might be intentional, somebodies idea of how 'real life' works.<FONT face="arial, helvetica" size="2"><br>
__________________<br>
Fadetree<br>
Ranger of Tunare, Fennin Ro</font></p>
